entry.title: [SPC] Allow 'publickey-credentials-create' for SPC creation
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/ab904a46 added the ability to use the

'publickey-credentials-create' permissions policy for WebAuthn

credential creation in a cross-origin iframe. However, if the

credential was for SPC (i.e., has the "payment" extension

specified), it still required the 'payment' permission policy.



This CL changes it so that SPC credential creation can occur in a

cross-origin iframe that has *either* the 'payment' (for backwards

compatibility) or 'publickey-credentials-create' policy.



In order to have content/browser/webauth/webauth_browsertest.cc

cover SPC credential creation, we needed //content to have some

sort of PaymentCredential mojo service. As such, this CL also adds

a stub PaymentCredential service for //content (which is overridden

with the real version for //chrome). This has the side effect of

making a WPT test start passing (as it was only failing due to the

lack of a //content hook for the given mojo API).



The change is still behind the

WebAuthnAllowCreateInCrossOriginFrame flag.



Bug: 1512605

entry.title: Reland "android: Make arm64 builds HighEnd by default"
entry.content:
This reverts commit af43747f42b8e4cd92542c69abb06d66eecc03df.



Reason for reland: Bot's updated with checkout_pgo_profiles=True



Original change's description:

> Revert "android: Make arm64 builds HighEnd by default"

>

> This reverts commit 0f58e5ed22c50498c4122491520b0720b38c0150.

>

> Reason for revert: Breaking internal CQ. E.g.:

> https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/try/android-internal-binary-size/26090/overview

>

> Original change's description:

> > android: Make arm64 builds HighEnd by default

> >

> > The most popular arm64 builds (Trichrome) are shipping with

> > is_high_end_android. The Monochrome arm64 builds are shipped for old

> > devices, and we expect these to gradually become less popular.

> >

> > This change sets is_high_end_android to true for arm64 builds by

> > default.

> >

> > This would make local benchmarking slightly less error prone because

> > there would be a little less to remember to set in GN args when making a

> > build for the most popular official configuration.

> >

> > Known effects:

> >

> > 1. Seemingly all official arm64 builders now explicitly set

> > is_high_end_android. Hence no effect for them.

> >

> > 2. Non-official arm64 builders will change to become high-end, even the

> > ones that end up running on old devices (example: android-arm64-rel).

> > In this patch we make sure that is_high_end_android is ignored for

> > non-official builds (disabled RELR relocations for non-official).

> > Hence, no effect here as well.

> >

> > 3. Official builds of Monochrome made by devs would fail to run on

> > Android pre-P (because RELR support is lacking). This leads to

> > mysterious crashes during something-dlopen in the Android dynamic

> > linker. Hopefully nobody does this before we remove support for

> > Android O.

| uniq \

| grep \

entry.title: Fix the permanent back trapping using same document entries
entry.content:
This fix enhances the history manipulation intervention such that

same document entries cannot be used to achieve permanent back trapping.

The original intervention stops working when there is a user activation

which does not get cleared after the user goes back and forth between

same document entries. So creating new same document entries becomes a

way to hijack the back button. This enhancement fixes the following

scenario:

1. History contains [new-tab-page, a*]

2. A gets a click and adds a same-document entry a1 =>

[new-tab-page, a, a1*]

3. User goes back to a via the back button

[new-tab-page, a*, a1]

4. Without any new user activation, a adds another new same document

entry a2. Page a should now be marked as skippable.

[new-tab-page, a(skip), a2*]

5. Now when the user goes back, they should land on new-tab-page.

entry.title: Ozone/Wayland: update window geometry on updated window scale
entry.content:
When frames advance, WaylandWindow updates its latched state that has

different state information such as raster scale, bounds_dip,

window_scale, etc.



Prior to this CL, the geometry was only updated whenever bounds were

updated. However, there is misconfiguration between the border insets

and the latched state. When Aura provides frame insets, they are

converted using current device scale factor, which can be different from

the `window_scale` that current `latched_state` has. As a result, the

geometry is set only for the very first frame when old latched state had

not real bounds. As a result, the geometry was set with insets in px as

it didn't know the correct `window_scale`.



This change fixes the behaviour by making WaylandWindow also update

geometry whenever `window_scale` changes. That way, the geometry stays

correct.



One of the visible bugs that this change fixes is wrongly positioned

popups. That is, the popups are positioned relatively to the parents'

geometry. And if the geometry was first set using wrong window scale

(eg in px, left: 32, top: 32), then xdg_positioner would have positioned

popups using that geometry in mind... While correct geometry in DIP that

should have been sent to Wayland compositor, should have been value /

scale.

entry.content:
The point of this IDL is to help fuzz the code base from a renderer POV

(understand, as if the renderer would be compromised).

without the need to depend on all of them at compile time (since

`third_party/blink/renderer/modules` can be limited regarding its deps).

See crrev.com/c/5134508 for a thorough example on how this works.

entry.title: Fix ImeClientDelegate memory leak by properly implementing Destroy().
entry.content:
Current contract between IME Service Container (here in Chromium repo)

and CrOS 1P IME Shared Lib (internal repo) is that ImeClientDelegate

instance is created by the former but the ownership is then transferred

to the latter [1] who should be in charge of memory cleanup.

This is rightfully already being done by the IME Shared Lib, but

unfortunately that's futile, as Destroy() is no-op [3], hence the leak.

entry.title: Check forms by signature for Android prefill requests.
entry.content:
The decision whether to send a prefill request is currently made

predominantly based on server predictions - they serve as a key

input to the FormDataParser used to predict whether the current form

is a login form.



This CL therefore introduces an experiment in which the decision whether

the currently focused form is similar to the previously cached form

is made based on FormSignatures. After all, these form signatures

decide which server predictions are queried.



Since form signatures are a hash of a subset of the members used in the

form similarity check, this should be a weaker condition that the

currently used call to FormDataAndroid::SimilarFormAs. A potential

further improvement loosening of the similarity check could be to run

FormDataParser again if the focused form has a different signature from

the cached one and, if the PWM-related form type and form field type

predictions match those of the cached form, still offer a bottom sheet.

entry.title: [SWAutoPreload] Handle MojoResult from the SimpleWatcher callback
entry.content:
ServiceWorkerRaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient::ReadAndWrite() is

registered as the callback of SimpleWatcher in this class. This is

called when both read/write data pipes are available to use.



Before this CL, the argument in the function was just not used at all

(and there was a typo). This CL adds the check and returns early if the

result is not a success response. The callback can take three types of

MojoResult patterns according to the doc[1]. We expect 99+% results are

|MOJO_RESULT_OK|, but adds UMA to capture for the monitoring purpose.



Actually, it shouldn't be a problem to ignore this result check because

we also have a MojoResult check when performing read/write operations in

each phase. But it's better to handle this case just in case.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:mojo/public/cpp/system/simple_watcher.h;l=37-52

entry.content:

minSdkVersion.

class REQUIRES_ANDROID_API(x)

is short for:

class __attribute__((__availability__(android, introduced = x)))



#pragma clang attribute push DEFAULT_REQUIRES_ANDROID_API(29)

is short for:

#pragma clang attribute push(__attribute__((__availability__(android, introduced = x))), apply_to = any(enum, enum_constant, field, function, namespace, record, type_alias, variable))



The new warnings (from -Wunguarded-availability) triggered in only two

spots: aaudio_stream_wrapper.cc, and ndk_media_codec_wrapper.cc



This commit converts these two files from explicit dlopen() / dlsym()
